segments.text: to do with selecting the new members.
As you think back, was the group rather select in its quality?
Yes, I think so.
A lot of people looked on it that were not members as sort of a fraternity.
And as you think back, was there any part of the, any unit of the Corps that had more than its share of RV members?
I don't think so.
There were some that really didn't have much.
I don't remember that there were an awful lot of fellows from the infantry.
I just, I don't remember that.
In the Corps in your day, was there any part of the Corps that supposedly was the most distinguished, the best students, or the most admired?
I think not.
I think in each regiment, though, there might have been a troop, a battery, or a company.
Where, for example, in Sea Battery Coast is where we call them the eggheads.
They seem like to be the best students of the bunch.
Was there anything at the bottom of the list that was supposed to be?
No, I don't think so.
And you were in the outfit you were in almost by accident?
Sure.
Okay.
Let's see.
Go back to the routine of the day.
When you weren't in class during the day, where did you go?
Well, if you were a freshman, you went back to the dormitory to be available to run details.
Okay.
Could you hide out in the library?
No.
You only could go to the library if you had permission.
and you'd have to put it on your door if you were a freshman, at least in my outfit.
I had permission from Mr. So-and-so to go to the library.
Where could you get a Coca-Cola?
Casey's in the basement of the YMCA was a drugstore sort of thing you could get if you had any money.
There was nothing at the North Gate.
Then describe dining.
Well, they was based on the Army ration, so we were told in those days.
I don't know of anybody that ever starved to death, but it was something less than the best.
Where did you eat?
I ate at Sabisa.
Describe a meal for a freshman.
Well, then we all ate the same thing.
You had assigned tables.
You marched in, and you sat down.
And the freshmen served, the upperclassmen.
And then the freshmen served themselves.
And every article of food, of course, had a name.
Sheriff the Chair.
Well, bread was gun whiting.
Dessert was kush.
Salt and pepper was sand and nothing.
You didn't call it anything by its name.
If the food was considered inedible, it was served family style, both.
a senior, a senior, who would sit at the head of the table, take that bowl, and here's a big passageway out there, and he'd put it out in the middle of the floor.
And the waiters, who were students, they were called Sabisa volunteers, treated with great respect and reverence and told about it.
They're waiters, but they're working their way through school, and you treat them with utmost respect.
So nobody, because they had to work, was made to feel like they were any less.
Very democratic.
But now, you lost me on.
Well, and they'd pick it up.
Oh, okay.
These waiters would pick it up and take it away.
All right, what was, do you remember any real favorite food, Sabisa food of yours?
No.
What was the worst?
Friday at noontime.
What was it?
Fish.
Fish.
Because in those days, it was required that the Catholics eat fish on Friday.
Did you all have a name for it?
I can't remember the name of it.
All I know is I couldn't go in the mess hall.
I could march down to the door, but I couldn't.
The smell of it just was so offensive to me.
Even when Sugar and I were married, she never cooked fish in the house because it made me sick.
All right, then, what about drills?
Where and how?
We had the drill field there in front of the Memorial Student Center.
Okay.
But it wasn't just restricted.
There was a lot of open space around.
How often did you all drill?
Once a week in your outfit, and sometimes more.
For how long was that?
Well, a couple hours, and some afternoon.
And wearing what?
Uniform.
Everybody wore a uniform every day.
Every day.
Every day.
Every day.
All right.
Now it's weekend.
And during your four years, where could y'all go for a good time?
No place.
There were two places.
I can't remember.
Hardlickers was one.
It was down past where Kyle Field is on the road to Weldon.
Can you describe Hardlickers?
Well, it was just a beer joint.
Typical, true to form, beer joints.
And what was the favorite beer of undergraduates then?
I don't know, Jack's was in Pearl and whatever.
John Lindsay thought it would be Grand Prize.
Grand Prize.
See, he's a Houstonian.
Yeah, that's right.
There was a Grand Prize brewery in Houston.
As a matter of fact, the Grand Prize brewery in Houston opened their gates when there was an A&M Court trip to Houston.
and the court took advantage of it.
Go out there and get free beer.
Was it permissible for y'all to drink beer at Hard Liquors?
Sure.
That was not contrary to any?
No.
Do you remember any 18 or older or 21 or older?
No.
No.
I don't think there was at that time.
No, in the first place, not very many out there because it cost money.
And most of the kids were like me.
They were too poor to even have a bag.
Who was in there other than Aggies?
Nobody.
Oh, as far as I know.
So it was almost all male.
Yeah.
Well, all weekends there would be some gals in there.
All right.
And what did you all call the place west of the river where you could buy alcohol?
I don't remember.
We called it across the river.
It wasn't called Whiskey Bridge then?
I had no recollection of it.
It was at Easley Beach.
It was on the other side of Bryce Road.
How often did y'all go to Bryant?
Again, it depended.
See, called quarters was at 7.30, 7 o'clock, 7.30.
And you could only, there was one night a week.
Right back where Puryear and Long were was a, we called it the...
Gosh, I can't remember what it was.
It was a theater there.
And they showed movies, and they were not every night of the week, one night of the week.
It just wasn't easy to, you couldn't be out as a freshman or sophomore in my outfit after call to court without permission.
Couldn't go to the library without permission.
You couldn't do anything.
What kind of activities occurred at Guyon Hall?
None to my recollection.
I only remember being there one time.
So there weren't movies?
I'm not saying there weren't movies.
I don't remember.
All I remember is that's where you got the message, look to your right, look to your left.
Now only one of the three of you will be here four years from now.
When was that message?
Fish induction day.
Was that when all of you were first brought together?
Correct.
Did you take, was there any ceremony or?
No, there were no fish camps in those days.
Okay.
You just were told to be down there and that's where the big assembly building was.
It was down at one end of the military wall, some beach at the other end.
When you arrived, did you know the Aggie War Hymn and the spirit?
No, you learned those pretty quickly.
The South Forks are pretty quick teachers.
Okay.
Let's see.
The easier you learn, the easier it is.
When did you like A&M from the beginning?
I like some things about it.
I can't imagine anybody liking A&M your first year or even your second year.
You just were nothing.
Nothing.
But you didn't leave.
No.
Yeah, lots left.
No, but you did.
No, but there were 45 freshmen, as I recall, in Mount Mary.
And some drop out the first week.
When things started clouding up, they had enough.
Then you get your mid-semester report card.
And grades, and if you're not there, they kick you out of school.
And so a lot would leave at that time.
All I'm saying is that there were 45 freshmen when we graduated, there were 12 seniors.
So one, in our numbers, a fourth in your outfit.
My outfit, yeah.
Graduated on time in four years.
As a matter of fact, every senior that was in my outfit didn't graduate in four years.
My roommate, for example, he was still taking calculus.
Was your roommate the same four years?
No, no, no.
No, he didn't graduate in four years.
I don't know if he graduated in five.
Did you have a special, special Aggie undergraduate friend or friends?
Oh, yeah.
Tell me.
Well, curiously enough, they were not in my outfit.
They were in my regimen.
Joe Slicker was... S-L-I-C-K-E-R. Yeah.
He was captain of the RVs my senior year, or our senior year, and he was from Cisco, Texas, and they called him the Cisco Kid.
Then Dan Grant was from Dallas.
James J. Gallagher, his father worked for the Katy Railroad, was from Smithville.
He died two months ago.
And myself.
And...
We were awfully close, very, very close.
And what brought you together?
I don't know.
We were all in the RVs for one thing.
We were all in the same regiment.
We went to summer camp.
We bought a car together.
Oh, it cost us $30.
It was a 29 Packard.
Wouldn't we like to have it now?
Lord have mercy.
We sold it for $5.
It quit running.
We just left it on the street.
And it was picked up by the sheriff or somebody.
And somebody came by, I remember our senior year, at dinner time.
And they said, Mayo, are you one of the owners of Blue Packard?
I said, yeah.
I said, where is it?
He said, well, the police have it.
He said, do you all want to sell it?
I said, well, sure.
So the others were nearby.
Those three were all in D batter.
I don't know.
Well, first of all, Dan Grants had a nickname.
His nickname was Snuffy.
It was Joseph Slicker, Joseph Gallagher.
And my middle name was Joseph.
So we had Joe, Joe, Joe, and Snuffy.
And we were the owners of that Packerdog.
Was Derwood T. Varner one of your?
No, Woody Varner?
He was ahead of us.
Woody Varner was the, he was a corps commander.
My recollection is Wayne Stark was a regimental commander at the Coastal Territory
while I was there.
I forget whether he was in the class of 38 or 39, I forget, maybe the 39 class, but I knew Woody Varner and saw Woody Varner after the war.
As a matter of fact, after I came back from Washington, I saw him in Dallas.
He was on the board of some big company, but I never had any society with him, no social
My recollection of a little bit of homework is that he was an outstanding student in almost every measurable way.
Well, that's one reason why he was a cadet colonel.
I don't remember his class.
Let's see, we asked about memorable, of your four years, were there some important teachers, advisors, important in shaping your life?
I don't think so.
Who'd you go to for advice?
Nobody.
In those days, you never talked to professors.
It was brown nosy.
So if you did that, and you just didn't do it, it was a no-no.
When the seniors in my regiment went on active duty,
We went to Fort Monroe, Virginia to artillery school.
And after that, we were sent to two different regiments at Fort Bliss, Texas.
And I wound up in the 63rd Coastal Artillery.
This is before I transferred to the field.
And there were 17 second lieutenants from my class assigned to that regiment.
16 of them classmates of mine.
There were 63 officers in that regiment.
Yeah, 63, all West Pointers are Thomason Act officers, or some officers that had been reserved, had been called to active duty, and then this group of second lieutenants.
When I got there where there were no OCS men, some came later out of that number one, number two, number three class.
Boy, now you talk about soldiers and officers.
They were, or they wouldn't have been in those early OCS classes.
In any event,
I was in that regiment until September 1942.
And when I left, I was 1st Lieutenant, and I went by to pay my respects to the regimental commander, Popsky.
We didn't call him Pop.
He was a bird carol.
When the war started, he was a bird carol.
He just passed over.
And we had a little visit to the regimental headquarters, and I told him what a pleasure it had been and a privilege to serve in his regiment.
And I think that everybody held him in utmost respect and so forth.
He said, I want to tell you something.
He said, I know when this Aggie crowd hit this regiment.
I remember it well.
It was before the war.
Everybody looking down their nose at you.
Why don't you second lieutenant from that Texas A&M?
Hey, this is Wes Warner talking.
And he said,
I'm losing all of you now.
I said, I want to tell you that the first thing that I noticed, there wasn't an ass kisser among you.
And I told him, I said, that was a no-no.
It's good.
I said, we called it in very vulgar terms and so forth.
And I said, you called it ass kissing?
And I said, yeah.
We just didn't do it.
Life would have been a hell if anybody ever saw you or heard that you had talked to a professor.
Absolutely not.
This was a terrible thing, but it was true.
While you were a student, did students ever have a real physical fight?
I never saw.
Two Aggies fight.
I understand they do it now sometimes.
I heard of a couple involving the football team.
Let's see, did I ask you about any kind of unique prank, Good Bull stunts that y'all heard of?
No, other than airing out and floating.
Religious activities on the campus?
Some.
Where?
What sort?
Well, none on the campus.
That chapel hadn't been built in those days.
But there were churches down at Northgate.
Did many students go?
I don't think so.
I didn't.
DeWare, what happened at DeWare Fieldhouse?
Well, of course it was there and it's torn down now.
But it was very much standing.
And I know Charlie DeWare.
It was named after his father.
But DeWare is a long time Ackie family.
There was no, what's the basketball stadium now that they've just turned the lights out?
G. Raleigh.
G. Raleigh wasn't there.
But tell me about DeWare.
Was it big?
Did you think?
No, but when you got there, did it seem big or little?
It just was a gym.
Okay.
And did you ever go over there?
Sure.
Sure.
We had intramurals there.
Intramural basketball was in DeWare.
And that's where the Aggies played.
Yeah.
Did a student ever get involved in intramurals?
What do you mean, get involved?
Did you ever participate?
Oh, listen, it was very important.
See, I'm asking you with a straight face.
Yeah, well, it was very important in those days.
The 54 batteries, troops, and companies were divided into leagues, and we played softball, football, a game called speedball.
swimming, diving, track, volleyball, horseshoe, water polo.
There were eight or nine intramural activities and one outfit was declared the intramural champion for the year.
A very coveted thing.
Was it considered a kind of a booby prize to be last?
I don't know that it was a booby prize, because we didn't permit that in our outfit.
We were one and two.
We were just strong.
What were the major optional student activity groups?
Tell me about the Aggie band.
Well, of course, the band was central to everything, as it is now, as far as the Corps is concerned, or even the university.
Was it similar to, who was the band director?
It was probably the roughest, toughest outfit on any pole.
Who was the band director?
Well, Colonel Toler's processer.
I can't remember his name.
Singing cadets?
Singing cadets, yes.
And where did they perform?
I don't know.
Just where they do now, I guess.
I really don't know.
I don't know that I ever heard of them more than once or twice.
Was there a student government?
No.
No, the Corps was the government.
You were talking about elections a while ago.
Tell them about student elections.
Well, they were just hat-card elections.
You had a student body president, as I recall, and certainly I know you had a president of each of the classes.
I'm not sure that we had a student body president.
I doubt that we did.
I think we just had class presidents.
But I'm not sure about that.
That was 57 years ago.
Now, this hat cord, tell me about it.
Well, the infantry wore blue hat cards, and they voted the way they were told to vote.
We wore red hat cards.
We voted the way we were told to vote.
And where did they tell you how to vote?
Well, right out in the broad daylight.
They stood there and watched you vote.
Where was the poll?
In the academic building, in the old tunnel there.
And the seniors would meet ahead of us and decide the alliances between the regiments and who they were going to vote for.
Events during the year.
R.B.
's was a very important weekend.
You did it during the Easter holidays when they left the campus.
It was Thursday, Friday, Saturday, Sunday, you're back in school on Monday
The whole student body left the campus, except certain foreign countries or whatever.
Kids couldn't get away.
And that's when the RVs had the run of the campus.
We had national bands come.
We had a tea dance on Saturday afternoon, for example.
It's a piece of it.
And now this initiation that you talked about, that occurred early in April?
Yes.
And then the Easter break, that weekend, came after that.
Well, that's right.
You were a full company then.
It might have been before the first of April.
Could have been in March.
Okay.
And was there a bonfire?
Sure.
Where?
Well, it was over on the other side of the railroad tracks, but it was not organized like it is now.
There was no way.
Well, what did you all burn up?
Just scrap wood.
Oh, they went out and collected wood.
Where did they get it?
Various places, and we never built an outhouse.
You mean there was an outhouse on there each year?
Each year.
It came from North Bride.
Different outfits.
Went into North Moraine with a rope and a truck and pulled one down and loaded it up in back of the truck and put it up on top of the mine fire and burned it.
Which, what students normally gathered most of the material?
Well the underclassmen.
The seniors didn't do anything.
Okay, let's see.
Then was there midnight yell practice?
Sure.
Before ever ball game.
Held?
For the Y.
That's where all of y'all practiced.
Okay.
Silver Taps, tell me about that.
Yes.
Describe Silver Taps.
Well, it's like it is today, except that everybody was there.
Everybody was there.
What did?
Since most of them I lived on campus, you see.
And I've gone out to Silver Taps there, Mitchell Hall my junior and senior year, in my pajamas and a rope.
Just standing there because you're right there by the academic building.
What did it mean to your heart?
It meant a lot to everybody.
Very important.
Very important.
Make believe that I had never heard of or seen Silver Taps.
Describe it for me.
Well, name, of course, for a student who had died since the last time he was out and was posted at the base of the flagpole in front of the academic building.
So we knew who it was.
Better remember the battalion was just published once a week in those days, not daily.
And just before it got around, I think it was all Tuesday like it is now, and we had to do silver taps.
And the RVs did not participate in it like it is now.
And everybody just gathered there in front of the academic building.
the whole cover, and they played the taps just the same as they do today.
Nothing was ever said, no words, everything was very hushed.
And after the silver taps played in each of the directions they played, it's all over.
You just go back to your room.
Your hole, we called it.
All Britain Carillion was not there playing Christian hymns on the bells.
The RVs didn't march.
There was no rifle fire of any kind.
It just was a very quiet, dignified cellar.
Was there an Aggie muster?
Sure.
Where?
Well, let me tell you.
The muster was something that we talked about and in my day didn't do.
And they didn't do it for some time before me.
It was an old, old custom.
And then it just died.
You mean y'all didn't have a muster?
No, we did not.
We did not.
Then on Corregidor, somebody remembered muster, a bunch of Aggies, April 21, 1941.
Or it could have been 42.
And it was revived then.
And the word just spread throughout the Pacific Theater of Operations.
And we had one on Okinawa in April 1945.
They had them in Europe.
The Army commander, Vinegar Joe Stillwell, the commanding general of the 10th Army on Okinawa.
We landed on Okinawa on Easter Sunday.
Aggie Pro-1, 1945, with 100,000 Japanese on it now.
Bloodiest battle in the Pacific.
Four Army divisions and two Marine divisions.
And on the 21st of April, there was a muster.
And an order came down from Army headquarters, from Vinegar Joe Stillworth.
If possible, Aggies can be temporarily relieved.
We're fighting the Japanese.
from their duties to attend their muster.
And they had coordinates of a road junction.

And guys, since you start showing up in Jeeps, they just parking here and there, and we got out of the Jeeps, we all made a circle, held hands, sang the spirit of Aggieland, got back in our Jeeps, went back to back to Japanese.
And of course, we're not all there.
I mean, all the Aggies weren't there.
was a very important time.
First muster I ever attended.
Okay, let's go back to the campus now.
You graduate in the spring of 1941.
Correct.
What world or national events during your undergraduate days do you remember kind of catching your attention?
Well, I think it depended on who you were.
What caught my attention was that war was imminent.
was a subject matter of my speech on Mother's Day.
I don't say I was more in tune with it, but others were.
Plus the fact that I came in from class in April, I think it was, early, early April, maybe mid-April.
And the first sergeant said, here's a letter for you.
I said, when did you start?
picking up my mail.
I had two room orders.
He said, this didn't come through the post office.
It came through the commandant's office.
It was ordering me and a whole host of others to active duties.
And we were listed in there, given Army serial numbers.
We were listed alphabetically where we were to go and when.
I didn't make final review my senior year.
We were at Fort Monroe, Virginia.
Had a special exercise for a

two or three hundred of us one week before, and a special commissioning exercise for us ahead of regular graduation and commissioning time, because we had to be at various places, Fort Monroe and some other place, on the very day that the final review was scheduled.
Where were those ceremonies held, that commissioning and commencement for you all, do you remember?
Who came to that?
Did your mother come?
Oh my Lord, no.
My mother was on the campus one time.
That was Mother's Day, my senior year.
Some parents perhaps were there.
So this was not a big event?
No, no it wasn't.
Not like they have today.
So those of us that were on those orders had said,
The following named second lieutenants, upon satisfactory completion of their academic work and being commissioned and so forth, are hereby ordered to active duty for one year.
And of course this was, we're talking about April 1941.
Then in May of 1941 it became a reality.
In the meantime,
The draft was started in 1940.
The National Guard was federalized in 1940.
September of 39, the war in Europe started.
So hell, we were at A&M, we knew that there was a war going on.
Who did you all think would be the enemy?
